title: Computer Science & Programming
description: Introduction to computer science and programming using a high-level programming language. Covers problem-solving techniques, algorithms, and data structures.

title: Calculus I
description: Calculus of rational functions, limits, derivatives, applications of the derivative, antiderivatives, the definite integral with applications, mean value theorem, fundamental theorem of calculus, and numerical integration.

title: First Year Writing I
prerequisite: A TSI placement score of at least 340, and an essay score of at least a 4 on the TSI Writing Assessment; or a placement score of less than 340, and an ABE Diagnostic level of at least 4, and an essay score of at least 5 on the TSI Writing Assessment; and a score ranging from 351 to 390 on the TSI Reading Assessment. Students may exempt the TSI by obtaining satisfactory scores on other accepted standardized tests. See http://www.uh.edu/ussc/tsi/ for details.
description: Introduction to the principles of writing with an emphasis on expository and argumentative essays.
note: Students who score below the minimum on the TSI must enroll concurrently in ENGL 1300 or, if slightly below the minimum writing score, in ENGL 1100. Students who score below the minimum on the TSI Reading Assessment must enroll concurrently in IRW 1300.

title: US History
description: Survey of American history from the earliest times to the present, focusing on significant historical events, figures, and movements.

title: Language, Philosophy, and Culture
description: Exploration of language, philosophy, and cultural contexts through various readings and critical analysis.

title: Introduction to Programming
description: Introduction to programming concepts, including data types, control structures, functions, and debugging techniques.

title: Calculus II
prerequisite: MATH 2413 with a grade of C- or higher.
description: Calculus of transcendental functions: additional techniques and applications of integration, indeterminate forms, improper integrals, Taylorâ€™s formula, and infinite series.

title: First Year Writing II
description: Detailed study of the principles of rhetoric as applied to analyzing and writing argumentative and persuasive essays; principles and methods of research, culminating in writing a substantial research paper.
note: Credit may not be received for both ENGL 1302 and ENGL 1310 or ENGL 1370.

title: Computer Org. & Architecture
description: Study of computer organization and architecture, including data representation, CPU architecture, memory hierarchy, and instruction sets.

title: Discrete Mathematics
description: Introduction to discrete mathematical structures, including logic, set theory, combinatorics, graph theory, and algorithms.

title: US Gov't: Congress, President, & Courts
description: Study of the American governmental system with a focus on the legislative, executive, and judicial branches.

title: Creative Arts
description: Introduction to creative arts through various media and methods, exploring artistic expression and interpretation.

title: Natural Science Lecture
description: Approved natural science lecture course designed to provide a foundational understanding of scientific principles and methods.

title: Programming & Data Structures
description: Advanced programming concepts and data structures including arrays, linked lists, stacks, queues, trees, and graphs.

title: Linear Algebra
description: Study of vector spaces, linear transformations, matrices, determinants, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors.

title: US & TX Constitution & Politics
description: Overview of the U.S. and Texas constitutions and the political systems including structure, functions, and processes.

title: Social & Behavioral Sciences
description: Exploration of various social and behavioral science concepts and methodologies.

title: Algorithms & Data Structures
description: In-depth study of algorithms and data structures including sorting, searching, and algorithm design techniques.

title: Database Systems
description: Study of database design, implementation, and management including relational databases, SQL, and normalization.

title: Statistics for Sciences
description: Introduction to statistical methods and data analysis for scientific research, including probability, hypothesis testing, and regression.

title: Writing in the Disciplines
description: Advanced writing course focusing on writing within specific disciplines and professional contexts.

title: Fundamentals of Operating Systems
description: Introduction to operating system concepts including process management, memory management, file systems, and concurrency.

title: Fund. of Software Engineering
description: Fundamental concepts of software engineering including software development lifecycle, requirements analysis, and design methodologies.
note: Credit may not be received for both COSC 4351 and COSC 4353.

title: COSC Advanced Elective
description: Advanced elective courses in computer science that focus on specialized topics and emerging technologies.

title: Intro. to Automata & Computability
description: Introduction to theoretical computer science including automata theory, formal languages, and computability.

title: Physical Chemistry I
description: Introduction to the principles of physical chemistry, including thermodynamics, kinetics, quantum chemistry, and spectroscopy. Emphasis on the mathematical treatment of physical chemistry concepts.

title: University Physics II Lab
description: Laboratory experiments to complement PHYS 2326. Topics include electromagnetism, optics, and modern physics experiments.

title: US Gov't: Congress, President, & Courts
description: Examination of the structure, functions, and processes of the United States government, focusing on Congress, the Presidency, and the Courts. Includes discussions on public policy and federalism.

title: Language, Philosophy & Culture
description: Exploration of language, philosophical thought, and cultural analysis through various texts and media. Aims to develop critical thinking and interpretive skills.
tccns: TCCNS Equivalent: CORE Language, Philosophy & Culture

title: Creative Arts
description: Study of creative arts including visual arts, music, and theatre. Focuses on artistic expression, cultural contexts, and critical analysis.

title: Analytical Chemistry I
description: Principles and techniques of analytical chemistry, including quantitative analysis, spectroscopy, and chromatography. Focus on chemical equilibria and error analysis.

title: Analytical Chemistry I Lab
description: Laboratory work to accompany CHEM 3369, emphasizing practical skills in analytical techniques and data interpretation.

title: US & Texas Constitution & Politics
description: Analysis of the United States and Texas constitutions, including their historical development, political principles, and current issues in state and federal politics.

title: Capstone or Advanced Elective
description: Capstone project or advanced elective in Natural Sciences and Mathematics. Includes research, analysis, and presentation of scientific or mathematical work.
tccns: TCCNS Equivalent: NSM Capstone or Advanced Elective

title: Foreign Language
description: Intermediate-level foreign language course focusing on enhancing language skills, including speaking, reading, writing, and listening.

title: Advanced Chemistry Electives
description: Advanced elective courses in Chemistry, focusing on specialized topics and advanced concepts within the field.

title: Capstone or Elective
description: Capstone project or elective in Natural Sciences and Mathematics. Includes research, analysis, and presentation of scientific or mathematical work.
tccns: TCCNS Equivalent: NSM Capstone or Elective

title: Introduction to Engineering
description: Introduction to engineering concepts, design, and problem-solving. Provides an overview of engineering professions and disciplines.

title: Biology for Science Majors I
description: Introduction to biological principles including cell biology, genetics, and evolution. Emphasis on the scientific method and biological research.

title: Biology for Science Majors I (lab)
description: Laboratory course accompanying BIOL 1306. Includes experiments and practical applications of biological concepts.

title: First Year Writing I
description: Focuses on the fundamentals of academic writing, including the writing process, grammar, and composition. Emphasizes critical reading and analytical skills.

title: Fundamentals of Chemistry
description: Introduction to chemical principles including atomic theory, chemical bonding, and stoichiometry. Includes an overview of the periodic table and chemical reactions.

title: Fundamentals of Chemistry Lab
description: Laboratory course accompanying CHEM 1311. Emphasizes hands-on experience with chemical experiments and techniques.

title: Calculus I
description: Introduction to differential calculus, including limits, derivatives, and applications of derivatives. Focus on functions and their properties.

title: Computing for Engineers
description: Introduction to computing techniques used in engineering, including programming, problem-solving, and numerical methods.

description: Continuation of BIOL 1306. Covers principles of ecology, evolution, and biodiversity. Includes a focus on the structure and function of plants and animals.

title: Biology for Science Majors II (lab)
description: Laboratory course accompanying BIOL 1307. Includes experiments related to ecology, evolution, and biodiversity.

description: Introduction to classical mechanics, including motion, forces, energy, and momentum. Emphasizes problem-solving and application of physical principles.

title: Fundamentals of Chemistry II
description: Continuation of CHEM 1311. Covers solutions, kinetics, equilibrium, thermodynamics, and electrochemistry.

title: Fundamentals of Chemistry II Lab
description: Laboratory course accompanying CHEM 1312. Includes experiments related to chemical reactions, equilibrium, and thermodynamics.

title: Calculus II
description: Continuation of Calculus I. Topics include integration techniques, applications of integrals, and sequences and series.

title: Intro to Biomedical Engineering
description: Introduction to biomedical engineering, including key concepts, career opportunities, and current trends in the field.

title: Organic Chemistry I
description: Introduction to organic chemistry, focusing on the structure, reactivity, and synthesis of organic molecules.

title: Organic Chemistry Lab I
description: Laboratory course accompanying CHEM 2323. Emphasizes practical techniques in organic synthesis and analysis.

title: Calculus III
description: Introduction to multivariable calculus, including partial derivatives, multiple integrals, and vector calculus.

title: University Physics II
description: Continuation of University Physics I. Topics include electromagnetism, optics, and modern physics.

title: First Year Writing II
description: Continued development of writing skills with a focus on research, argumentation, and advanced composition techniques.

description: Exploration of artistic expression through various media. Includes history, theory, and practice of the arts.
